.SH NAME
WordList \- Specification and base class for WordList::*, modules that contain word list
.SH VERSION
.IX Header "VERSION"
This document describes version 0.7.11 of WordList (from Perl distribution WordList), released on 2021\-09\-26.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
Use one of the \f(CW\*(C`WordList::*\*(C'\fR modules.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\f(CW\*(C`WordList::*\*(C'\fR modules are modules that contain, well, list of words. This
module, \f(CW\*(C`WordList\*(C'\fR, serves as a base class and establishes convention for such
modules.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`WordList\*(C'\fR is an alternative for Games::Word::Wordlist and
\&\f(CW\*(C`Games::Word::Wordlist::*\*(C'\fR. Its main difference is: \f(CW\*(C`WordList::*\*(C'\fR wordlists
are read\-only/immutable and the modules are designed to have low startup
overhead. This makes them more suitable for use in CLI scripts which often only
want to pick a word from one or several lists. See "DIFFERENCES WITH
GAMES::WORD::WORDLIST" for more details.
.PP
Unless you are defining a dynamic wordlist (see below), words (or phrases) must
be put in \f(CW\*(C`_\|_DATA_\|_\*(C'\fR section, one per line. Putting the wordlist in the
\&\f(CW\*(C`_\|_DATA_\|_\*(C'\fR section relieves perl from having to parse the list during the
loading of the module. To search for words or picking some random words from the
list, the module also need not slurp the whole list into memory (and will not do
so unless explicitly instructed).
.PP
You must sort your words ascibetically (or by Unicode code point). Sorting makes
it more convenient to diff different versions of the module, as well as
performing binary search. If you have a different sort order other than
ascibetical, you must set package variable \f(CW$SORT\fR with some true value (say,
\&\f(CW\*(C`frequency\*(C'\fR).
.PP
There must not be any duplicate entry in the word list.
.PP
\&\fBDynamic and non\-deterministic wordlist.\fR A dynamic wordlist must set package
variable \f(CW$DYNAMIC\fR to either 1 (deterministic) or 2 (non\-deterministic). A
dynamic wordlist does not put the wordlist in the DATA section; instead, user
relies on \f(CWfirst_word()\fR + \f(CWnext_word()\fR, or \f(CWeach_word()\fR, or \f(CWall_words()\fR
to get the list. A deterministic wordlist returns the same list everytime
\&\f(CWeach_word()\fR or \f(CWall_words()\fR is called. A non\-deterministic list can return
a different list for a different \f(CWeach_word()\fR or \f(CWall_words()\fR call. See
WordListRole::FirstNextResetFromEach,
WordListRole::EachFromFirstNextReset, WordListRole::FromArray if you want
to write a dynamic wordlist module. It is possible for a dynamic list to return
unordered or duplicate entries, but it is not encouraged.
.PP
\&\fBParameterized wordlist.\fR When instantiating a wordlist class instance, user
can pass a list of key\-value pairs as parameters. Normally only a dynamic
wordlist would accept parameters. Parameters are defined in the \f(CW%PARAMS\fR
package variable. It is a hash of parameter names as keys and parameter
specification as values. Parameter specification follows function argument
metadata specified in Rinci::function.
.PP
\&\fBExamples.\fR Examples can be specified in \f(CW@EXAMPLES\fR package variable. The
structure is similar to Rinci function\*(Aqs \f(CW\*(C`examples\*(C'\fR
property. For example:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& # in lib/WordList/Test/Dynamic/RandomWord/1000.pm
\&
\& @EXAMPLES = (
\&     {
\&         summary => \*(Aq1000 random words, each 10 to 15 characters long\*(Aq,
\&         args => {min_len=>10, max_len=>15},
\&     }
\& );
.Ve
.SH "DIFFERENCES WITH GAMES::WORD::WORDLIST"
.IX Header "DIFFERENCES WITH GAMES::WORD::WORDLIST"
Since this is a non\-compatible interface from Games::Word::Wordlist, I also make
some other changes:
.IP \(bu 4
Namespace is put outside \f(CW\*(C`Games::\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Because obviously word lists are not only useful for games.
.IP \(bu 4
Namespace is more language\-neutral and not English\-centric
.Sp
English wordlists are put under \f(CW\*(C`WordList::EN::*\*(C'\fR. Other languages have their
own subnamespaces, e.g. \f(CW\*(C`WordList::FR::*\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`WordList::ID::*\*(C'\fR. Aside from
language subnamespaces, there are also other subnamespaces:
\&\f(CW\*(C`WordList::Phrase::$LANG::*\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`WordList::Password::*\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`WordList::Domain::*\*(C'\fR,
\&\f(CW\*(C`WordList::HTTP::*\*(C'\fR, etc.
.IP \(bu 4
Interface is simpler
.Sp
This is partly due to the list being read\-only. The methods provided are just:
.Sp
\&\- \f(CW\*(C`pick\*(C'\fR (pick one or several random entries, without duplicates or with)
.Sp
\&\- \f(CW\*(C`word_exists\*(C'\fR (check whether a word is in the list)
.Sp
\&\- \f(CW\*(C`each_word\*(C'\fR (run code for each entry)
.Sp
\&\- \f(CW\*(C`all_words\*(C'\fR (return all the words in a list)
.Sp
A couple of other functions might be added, with careful consideration.
.IP \(bu 4
More extensions
.Sp
Some roles, subclasses, or alternate implementations are provided. For example,
since most wordlist are alphabetically sorted, a binary search can be performed
in \f(CWword_exists()\fR. There is a role, WordListRole::BinarySearch, that does
that and can be mixed in. An even faster version of \f(CWword_exists()\fR using bloom
filter is offered by WordListRole::Bloom. A faster version of \fBpick()\fR that
does random seeking is offered by WordListRole::RandomSeekPick.
.SH "SUBCLASSING OR CREATING ROLES"
.IX Header "SUBCLASSING OR CREATING ROLES"
If you want to get the word list from another filehandle source, e.g. a gzipped
file, you just need to override \f(CWreset_iterator()\fR. Your \f(CWreset_iterator()\fR
needs to set the \*(Aqfh\*(Aq attribute to the filehandle. The default \f(CWfirst_word()\fR
calls \f(CWreset_iterator()\fR and reads a line from the filehandle. The default
\&\f(CWnext_word()\fR just reads another line from the filehandle. \f(CWeach_word()\fR is
implemented in terms of \f(CWfirst_word()\fR and \f(CWnext_word()\fR, and
\&\f(CWword_exists()\fR, \f(CWpick()\fR, and \f(CWall_words()\fR are implemented in terms of
\&\f(CWeach_word()\fR.
.SH METHODS
.IX Header "METHODS"
.SS new
.IX Subsection "new"
Usage:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $wl = WordList::Module\->new([ %params ]);
.Ve
.PP
Constructor.
.SS each_word
.IX Subsection "each_word"
Usage:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $wl\->each_word($code)
.Ve
.PP
Call \f(CW$code\fR for each word in the list. The code will receive the word as its
first argument.
.PP
If code return \-2 will exit early.
.SS first_word
.IX Subsection "first_word"
Another way to iterate the word list is by calling "first_word" to get the
first word, then "next_word" repeatedly until you get \f(CW\*(C`undef\*(C'\fR.
.SS next_word
.IX Subsection "next_word"
Get the next word. See "first_word" for more details.
.SS reset_iterator
.IX Subsection "reset_iterator"
Reset iterator. Basically "first_word" is equivalent to \f(CW\*(C`reset_iterator\*(C'\fR +
"next_word".
.SS pick
.IX Subsection "pick"
Usage:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& @words = $wl\->pick([ $num=1 [ , $allow_duplicates=0 ] ])
.Ve
.PP
Examples:
.PP
.Vb 2
\& ($word) = $wl\->pick;
\& @words  = $wl\->pick(3);
.Ve
.PP
Pick \f(CW$n\fR (default: 1) random word(s) from the list, without duplicates (unless
\&\f(CW$allow_duplicates\fR is set to true). If there are less then \f(CW$n\fR words in the
list and duplicates are not allowed, only that many will be returned.
.PP
The algorithm used is from perlfaq ("perldoc \-q "random line""), which scans the
whole list once (a.k.a. \fBeach_word()\fR once). The algorithm is for returning a
single entry and is modified to support returning multiple entries.
.SS word_exists
.IX Subsection "word_exists"
Usage:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $wl\->word_exists($word) => bool
.Ve
.PP
Check whether \f(CW$word\fR is in the list.
.PP
Algorithm in this implementation is linear scan (O(n)). Check out
WordListRole::BinarySearch for an O(log n) implementation, or
WordListRole::Bloom for O(1) implementation.
.SS all_words
.IX Subsection "all_words"
Usage:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $wl\->all_words() => list
.Ve
.PP
Return all the words in a list, in order. Note that if wordlist is very large
you might want to use "each_word" instead to avoid slurping all words into
memory.
.SH FAQ
.IX Header "FAQ"
.SS "Why does \fBpick()\fP return ""1""?"
.IX Subsection "Why does pick() return ""1""?"
You probably write this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& $word = $wl\->pick;
.Ve
.PP
instead of this:
.PP
.Vb 1
\& ($word) = $wl\->pick;
.Ve
.PP
\&\f(CWpick()\fR returns a list and in scalar context it returns the number of elements
in the list which is 1. This is a common context trap in Perl.
